Certainly! Below is an example of how you can create a random walk graph using TikZ in LaTeX. This example will generate a simple random walk with 10 steps.

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=5]{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]
    % Define the starting point
    \coordinate (start) at (0,0);

    % Draw the initial point
    \filldraw[black] (start) circle (2pt);

    % Define step size
    \def\stepsize{1cm}

    % Generate random walk
    \foreach \i in {1,...,10} {
        % Random direction: 0, 90, 180, or 270 degrees
        \pgfmathsetmacro{\angle}{rnd * 360 / 4};

        % Calculate new position
        \pgfpointadd{\pgfpointanchor{start}{center}}{\pgfpointxy{\stepsize*cos(\angle)}{\stepsize*sin(\angle)}};

        % Update start point to new position
        \let\start\pgfresult

        % Draw line to new position
        \draw[->] (start -| start) -- (\start);

        % Draw dot at new position
        \filldraw[black] (\start) circle (2pt);
    }
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **`\coordinate (start)`**: Defines the starting point of the random walk.
- **`\filldraw[black] (start) circle (2pt)`**: Draws and fills a small black circle at the starting point.
- **`\foreach \i in {1,...,10}`**: Loops 10 times to generate 10 steps in the random walk.
